Inspiration
The modern job application process is fragmented, repetitive, and inefficient. Candidates juggle multiple job boards, duplicate listings, and inconsistent application tracking, often leading to wasted effort and missed opportunities. Most existing tools focus on surface-level organization or autofill convenience, but fail to address the deeper problem: managing applications as a structured, high-stakes workflow under real constraints.
We were inspired by the idea that applying to jobs should not be a manual, error-prone process, but a coordinated system that enforces correctness and efficiency. Instead of building another tracker, we set out to design a backend that acts as the source of truth for a user’s job search—preventing duplicate applications, enforcing limits, and maintaining a consistent record of every action.
Our goal was to treat job applications not as static entries, but as dynamic, stateful operations that require reliability, deduplication, and careful orchestration.

What It Does
Our system is an application orchestration API that manages the full lifecycle of job applications, from ingestion to submission to status tracking, while guaranteeing consistency under concurrent usage.
Rather than acting as a passive tracker, the system operates as a transactional engine:
Ingests job listings from multiple sources and deduplicates them into a single canonical record
Evaluates whether a user can apply based on constraints like prior applications and rate limits
Selects the appropriate resume version and locks it for consistency
Executes application submission as a transactional write
Maintains a strict state machine for each application (saved → applied → interview → offer/rejected)
Records all actions as immutable events for auditability
This design ensures that every application is accurate, non-duplicated, and consistent, even under concurrent requests or retries. By treating the database as the source of record and enforcing invariants at the API level, the system provides a reliable foundation for managing high-volume job searches.

